The paper proposes a novel framework for network embedding that utilizes attention mechanisms and adversarial regularization. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the sub-category of Machine Learning (cs.LG) as it involves the development of a new learning framework. Additionally, the paper deals with network analysis and representation, which could place it in the sub-categories of Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) and Sound and Music Computing (cs.SD). The use of multi-scale structure information and the focus on network embedding could also place the paper in the sub-category of Network Embedding (cs.NE). Finally, the use of adversarial regularization suggests that the paper could also belong to the sub-category of Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI).
